                <head>162. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>Under Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">Douglas Dillon</persName>
                    visited Yugoslavia July 17–20, during a five-nation good will tour. On July 18
                    at 9:30 a.m., <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName> met with Yugoslav
                    Vice President <persName corresp="#p_TM1">Todorovic</persName> (see <ref
                        target="#d163">Document 163</ref>). After lunch with <persName
                        corresp="#p_TM1">Todorovic</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_DCD1"
                        >Dillon</persName> visited the Pancevo fertilizer plant. That evening he
                    attended a dinner at the U.S. Embassy. At 11 a.m. on July 19, <persName
                        corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName> met with President <persName
                        corresp="#p_TMJB1">Tito</persName> at the latter’s villa on the island of
                    Vanga (see <ref target="#d164">Documents 164</ref>–<ref target="#d168"
                    >168</ref>). After his discussions with <persName corresp="#p_TMJB1"
                        >Tito</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName> returned to
                    the Yugoslav mainland and drove to Zagreb. <persName corresp="#p_DCD1"
                        >Dillon</persName> flew from Zagreb to Paris the morning of July 20.
                    Documentation on <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName>’s visit to
                    Yugoslavia, including memoranda of conversation, summary telegrams, and briefing
                    papers, is in Department of State, Conference Files: Lot 64 <gloss
                        target="#t_D1">D</gloss> 559, <gloss target="#t_CF1">CF</gloss> 1724.</p>
            </div>
